To find the Cartesian product of two sets, we form ordered pairs with the elements from the first set as the first component and the elements from the second set as the second component.

A × B = {(a, b) | a ∈ A, b ∈ B}
A × B = {(1, 2), (1, 3)}

B × A = {(b, a) | b ∈ B, a ∈ A}
B × A = {(2, 1), (3, 1)}

As we can see, A × B ≠ B × A, since the ordered pairs are different. This shows that the Cartesian product of two sets is not commutative with respect to union.
